  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../blog-posts/china-invests-billions-international-renewable-energy-projects">China Invests Billions in International Renewable Energy Projects</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"><img src="../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/kunming.jpg" alt="" title="" width="180" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p><i>This post <a href="http://insights.wri.org/news/2013/06/china-invests-billions-international-renewable-energy-projects">originally appeared</a> on WRI Insights.</i></p>

<p>It‚Äôs well-known that China ranks first in the world in attracting clean energy investment, <a href="http://www.pewenvironment.org/uploadedFiles/PEG/Publications/Report/-clenG20-Report-2012-Digital.pdf">receiving US$ 65.1 billion in 2012</a>.  But <a href="http://www.wri.org/publication/china-overseas-investments-in-wind-and-solar-trends-and-drivers">new analysis from WRI</a> shows another side to this story: China is increasingly becoming a global force in international clean energy investment, too.</p></div>
