  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../blog-posts/building-our-clean-energy-industries-learning-chinas-experience-wind-power">Building Our Clean Energy Industries: Learning from China‚Äôs experience in wind power</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"><img src="../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/JIL_020413_CoverPic.jpg" alt="" title="" width="192" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p>As the biggest coal-consuming and coal-producing nation in the world, China is perhaps an unlikely place to find a burgeoning wind power industry. Yet today China is the biggest wind power market in the world and builds almost all its wind turbines at home. China‚Äôs wind power capacity has increased over a hundredfold in the past decade (from 344 MW in 2000 to 44,733 MW in 2010) and estimates for 2012 put installed wind capacity at about 80 GW (see Figure 1).  Just a decade ago the country had only a handful of wind turbines in operation‚Äîall imported from Europe and the United States.</p></div>
