  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../blog-posts/china-increasingly-attractive-renewable-energy-investment">China Increasingly Attractive for Renewable Energy Investment</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"><img src="../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/solarpanels.jpg" alt="" title="" width="171" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p>China has remained the most attractive destination for clean energy investment for a full year, followed by the U.S., according to the most recent <a href="http://www.ey.com/Publication/vwLUAssets/Renewable_energy_country_attractiveness_indices_-_Issue_29/$FILE/EY_RECAI_issue_29.pdf">Renewable Energy Country Attractiveness Indices</a> compiled by consulting firm Ernst &amp; Young. The report showed China increasing its rating from 71 to 72 on a 100-point scale last quarter, followed by the U.S. unchanged at 67. As <a href="http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-25/china-widens-lead-in-renewable-energy-ranking-by-ernst-young.html">Bloomberg reports</a>, the report attributed China‚Äôs gain to its increased focus on offshore wind and concentrated solar power, in addition to new renewable energy targets in its <a href="../blog-posts/how-does-chinas-12th-five-year-plan-address-energy-and-environment">12th Five Year Plan</a>.</p></div>
  </div>
