  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../blog-posts/updates-tianjin-progress-greengen-igcc-project">Updates from Tianjin: Progress on the GreenGen IGCC project</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"><img src="../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/Li.JPG" alt="" title="" width="160" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p>Having the intercessional UN Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) meeting in China this week ‚Äì the last stop before ministers and heads of state meet in Cancun for the sixteenth Conference of Parties (COP-16) ‚Äì provides a timely opportunity for participants to witness firsthand elements of China‚Äôs clean energy and climate policies in action.</p></div>
  </div>
  </div>
  <div class="views-row views-row-110 views-row-even">
      
  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../blog-posts/ge-chair-jeff-immelt-criticizes-outdated-us-energy-policy-urges-better-us-regulatory-stru">GE Chair Jeff Immelt Criticizes Outdated US Energy Policy, Urges Better US Regulatory Structure and Support for Innovators to Expand Clean Energy</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p>The U.S. energy regulatory system is ‚Äúa relic of the 1860s‚Äù, according to Jeff Immelt, Chairman of GE, one of the World‚Äôs largest manufacturers of new clean energy technology.  In a conference in Washington, DC last week, he urged the U.S. government to take positive action in the United States to <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/cwire/2010/09/24/24climatewire-ges-immelt-says-us-policy-deadlock-holds-bac-86164.html">support clean technology</a>.  Yes, said Immelt, China is a competitor, <a href="http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748703384204575509760331620520.html#">but not just China</a>.  Countries such as Canada and Australia also ‚Äúhave much simpler regulatory structures for energy and are moving more quickly.‚Äù</p></div>
  </div>
  </div>
  <div class="views-row views-row-111 views-row-odd">
      
  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../blog-posts/us-china-strategic-and-economic-dialogue-pledges-greater-energy-market-transparency-and-e">US-China Strategic and Economic Dialogue: Pledges of Greater Energy Market Transparency and Energy Supply Diversification</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"><img src="../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/flag_5_26_10.jpg" alt="" title="" width="200" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p>Climate change was not the big news it was a year ago at the US-China Strategic and Economic Dialogue (S&amp;ED).  This is not surprising given that China made its major commitment on emissions reductions ‚Äì its 40-45% carbon intensity target by 2020 ‚Äì last year and US climate legislation is pending in the Senate.  But many of the key players on climate change, including Secretary of State Clinton, her Climate Negotiator Todd Stern, and Department of Energy Assistant Secretary David Sandalow, were at the meeting.   Energy Secretary Steven Chu stayed in the US to address the <a href="http://www.energy.gov/news/9001.htm">Gulf of Mexico oil spill</a>, but his Department co-hosted three major bilateral seminars on energy efficiency, renewable energy and biofuels after the S&amp;ED.</p></div>
  </div>
  </div>
  <div class="views-row views-row-112 views-row-even">
      
  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../library/chinafaqs-solar-energy">ChinaFAQs: Solar Energy</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"><img src="../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/ChinaFAQs_Solar_Energy.png" alt="" title="" width="93" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"><div class="filefield-file"><img class="filefield-icon field-icon-application-pdf"  alt="application/pdf icon" src="../sites/all/modules/filefield/icons/application-pdf.png" /><a href="../files/chinainfo/ChinaFAQs_Solar_Energy.pdf" type="application/pdf; length=276243">ChinaFAQs_Solar_Energy.pdf</a></div></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p><b>Key Points:</b></p>

<ul>
<li>China is rolling out policies, subsidies and R&amp;D programs aimed at encouraging the large-scale deployment of solar technologies ‚Äì including a joint project with an American company to build the world‚Äôs largest solar electricity plant in the Mongolian desert.</li>
<li>China is already the world‚Äôs largest manufacturer of solar photovoltaic cells, but most are exported. Now, it is moving to expand its domestic market.</li>
<li>China‚Äôs solar push is part of a larger effort to get at least 15% of its energy from renewable sources by 2020.</li>
</ul></div>
  </div>
  </div>
